    ],
    "claim": "`selfSwap()` is permissionless, and each route performs an unrestricted `router.call(...)`. An attacker can set `router = address(this)` and encode a nested call to `fill(...)`; because that external self-call arrives with `msg.sender == address(this)`, the `onlySelf` guard passes and the attacker reaches the relay settlement path without being a whitelisted relay. The nested `fill()` then pulls tokens from any `executionRequest.requester` that has approved Dexible and can forward them through attacker-controlled routes.",
    "impact": "Any external account can bypass the relay gate and drain ERC20 allowances from arbitrary victims who approved Dexible, turning what should be a relay-only flow into permissionless theft.",
    "paths": [
      "Attacker calls `selfSwap()` with an outer route whose `router` is `address(this)` and whose `routerData` encodes `fill(innerRequest, innerMeta)`.",
      "The nested `fill()` accepts an arbitrary `innerRequest.executionRequest.requester` and executes because `onlySelf` now sees `msg.sender == address(this)`.",
      "During `preCheck()`, Dexible pulls `innerRequest.routes[0].routeAmount.amount` from the victim, then approves/calls attacker-controlled route logic to move the tokens away."
    ]
  },
